A push is when you actively reach out to customers to get them to use your product, while a pull is when customers come to you on their own, often through word of mouth or other organic means.
In the context of Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD), a "push" refers to a situation where a company actively promotes a product or service to potential customers, often through marketing and advertising efforts. The company is essentially "pushing" the product onto the market and trying to convince people to buy it.

On the other hand, a "pull" in JTBD refers to a situation where customers actively seek out a product or service because they have a specific job they need to get done, and they believe that the product or service will help them accomplish that job. In this case, the customer's need or desire for the product "pulls" it into the market.

The error message suggests that there is an issue with the package declaration in your App.java file. It seems that the package declaration is not allowed at the location where it is currently placed in the file.

In Java, the package declaration should be the first line of code in the file (excluding comments and whitespace). Make sure that your App.java file follows this structure:
```
package com.mycompany.app;

public class App {
    // Your code here
}
```
Additionally, in your pom.xml file, you don't need to specify the App.java file as a dependency. Maven automatically compiles the source files located in the src/main/java directory.

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor's VCC and GND pins should be connected to the Arduino's power and ground, respectively. The analog output pin of the LM35 should be connected to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The first pin of the potentiometer should be connected to +VCC, the second pin to pin 3 of the LCD, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

The error message is telling you that the `using enum` feature requires C++20 or later. By default, Visual Studio uses an older version of the C++ standard.

To enable C++20 in Visual Studio, you can follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer.
2. Select "Properties" from the context menu.
3. In the Properties window, go to "Configuration Properties" > "C/C++" > "Language".
4. Set the "C++ Language Standard" option to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)".
5. Click "Apply" and then "OK" to save the changes.
